Note: ================================================================
Note: Bifrost Memory Access Analysis
Note: ================================================================
Note: Analyzes memory access patterns for GPU coalescing, cache locality,
Note: and optimal data layout. Detects opportunities for shared memory,
Note: identifies bank conflicts, and estimates bandwidth requirements.
Note: ================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/graph.runa" as Graph
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/node.runa" as Node
Import "compiler/middle/bifrost/graph/edge.runa" as Edge
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as String
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Math

Note: ================================================================
Note: Access Pattern Constants
Note: ================================================================

Constant ACCESS_UNKNOWN as Integer is 0
Constant ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS as Integer is 1       Note: Sequential, stride=1
Constant ACCESS_STRIDED as Integer is 2          Note: Regular stride>1
Constant ACCESS_RANDOM as Integer is 3           Note: Irregular pattern
Constant ACCESS_BROADCAST as Integer is 4        Note: Same value to all threads
Constant ACCESS_GATHER as Integer is 5           Note: Indexed read
Constant ACCESS_SCATTER as Integer is 6          Note: Indexed write

Note: ================================================================
Note: Memory Space Constants
Note: ================================================================

Constant MEMORY_GLOBAL as Integer is 0           Note: Main device memory (slow, large)
Constant MEMORY_SHARED as Integer is 1           Note: On-chip scratchpad (fast, small)
Constant MEMORY_LOCAL as Integer is 2            Note: Thread-local registers (fastest)
Constant MEMORY_CONSTANT as Integer is 3         Note: Read-only, cached, broadcast

Note: ================================================================
Note: Fixed-Point Scale (PPM = Parts Per Million)
Note: ================================================================
Note: Stage1 (v0.0.8.4.5.3.5) of the bootstrap chain does not yet implement
Note: floating-point literals or runtime float arithmetic. The Float type
Note: support is scheduled for v0.0.8.6. Until that lands, all fractional
Note: ratios in the Bifrost analysis passes are represented as fixed-point
Note: integers in parts-per-million (PPM), where 1_000_000 == 1.0.
Note:
Note: PPM example values:
Note:   PPM_ONE        == 1_000_000  (== 1.0)
Note:   PPM_HALF       == 500_000    (== 0.5)
Note:   PPM_TENTH      == 100_000    (== 0.1)
Note: ================================================================

Constant PPM_ONE as Integer is 1000000
Constant PPM_ZERO as Integer is 0

Note: ================================================================
Note: Type Definitions
Note: ================================================================

Type called "AccessPattern":
    pattern_type as Integer         Note: ACCESS_* constant
    stride as Integer               Note: Access stride in elements
    element_size as Integer         Note: Size of each element in bytes
    is_aligned as Boolean           Note: Whether accesses are aligned
    is_coalesced as Boolean         Note: Whether GPU accesses coalesce
End Type

Type called "MemoryFootprint":
    total_bytes as Integer          Note: Total memory required
    reads_bytes as Integer          Note: Bytes read
    writes_bytes as Integer         Note: Bytes written
    peak_usage as Integer           Note: Peak simultaneous usage
End Type

Type called "LocalityInfo":
    spatial_locality_ppm as Integer  Note: 0..1_000_000 PPM, higher is better
    temporal_locality_ppm as Integer Note: 0..1_000_000 PPM, higher is better
    cache_reuse_distance as Integer  Note: Average reuse distance in accesses
    working_set_size as Integer      Note: Working set size in bytes
End Type

Type called "CoalescingInfo":
    is_coalesced as Boolean              Note: Whether accesses coalesce
    coalescing_factor_ppm as Integer     Note: 0..1_000_000 PPM, 1_000_000 is perfect
    wasted_transactions as Integer       Note: Number of wasted memory transactions
    optimal_transactions as Integer      Note: Minimum possible transactions
End Type

Type called "BankConflictInfo":
    has_conflicts as Boolean        Note: Whether bank conflicts exist
    conflict_degree as Integer      Note: Max serialization factor
    conflict_pattern as Integer     Note: Pattern causing conflicts
End Type

Note: ================================================================
Note: Access Pattern Classification
Note: ================================================================

@Reasoning
Classifies memory access patterns for optimisation opportunities. The
classification feeds GPU coalescing analysis, prefetch insertion, cache
locality estimation, and shared-memory promotion decisions. Patterns are
CONTIGUOUS (stride 1, best for caches/coalescing), STRIDED (regular
stride > 1, predictable, may benefit from prefetch), RANDOM (irregular,
poor locality), BROADCAST (constant address, use constant memory),
GATHER (indirect read via index array), SCATTER (indirect write).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Initialises an AccessPattern struct with default UNKNOWN / stride=1 /
element_size=0 / is_aligned=false / is_coalesced=false. Reads the node
op_kind; bails out for non-memory ops (op_kind != 40 Load and != 41
Store). Extracts the address input node, fetches element_size via the
node's data type. Calls classify_address_pattern on the address subgraph
to get (pattern_type, stride), and writes them into the struct. Calls
check_alignment to determine is_aligned. Sets is_coalesced when the
pattern is CONTIGUOUS and the access is aligned. Returns the populated
AccessPattern.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(depth_of_address_DAG) time; visits each address-computation node once
via classify_address_pattern. Cold path during graph construction;
becomes hot when called per memory op during coalescing analysis.
Result is a small fixed-size struct so allocation pressure is minimal.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure analysis on already-validated graph nodes; trusts upstream graph
builders for node-kind invariants. No file I/O, no capability use.
Untrusted graphs (e.g. deserialized from disk) must be verified by
the upstream graph loader before calling this proc.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "analyze_access_pattern" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let access_pattern be a value of type AccessPattern with
        pattern_type as ACCESS_UNKNOWN,
        stride as 1,
        element_size as 0,
        is_aligned as false,
        is_coalesced as false

    Note: Get operation kind
    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with node

    Note: Load=40, Store=41
    Let is_memory_op be false
    If op_kind is equal to 40:
        Set is_memory_op to true
    End If
    If op_kind is equal to 41:
        Set is_memory_op to true
    End If

    If is_memory_op is equal to false:
        Return access_pattern
    End If

    Note: Get address computation (first input is address)
    Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
    If proc length from List with inputs is equal to 0:
        Return access_pattern
    End If

    Let address_node be proc get from List with inputs, 0

    Note: Get element size from data type
    Let data_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
    Let element_size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with data_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 16, element_size

    Note: Analyze address computation for pattern
    Let pattern_info be classify_address_pattern(graph, address_node)

    Note: Extract pattern type and stride
    Let pattern_type be proc get from List with pattern_info, 0
    Let stride be proc get from List with pattern_info, 1

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 0, pattern_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 8, stride

    Note: Check alignment (element size must be power of 2, address aligned)
    Let is_aligned be check_alignment(address_node, element_size)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 24, is_aligned

    Note: Check coalescing (contiguous + aligned + element size suitable)
    Let is_coalesced be false
    If pattern_type is equal to ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS:
        If is_aligned is equal to true:
            Set is_coalesced to true
        End If
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with access_pattern, 32, is_coalesced

    Return access_pattern
End Process

@Reasoning
Classifies the address computation pattern used by analyze_access_pattern.
Common patterns: base+index gives CONTIGUOUS (stride=1); base+index*stride
gives STRIDED; base+array[index] gives GATHER/SCATTER (indirect);
constant address gives BROADCAST; complex expressions give RANDOM. The
classifier checks each pattern in order of specificity (constant first,
affine next, indirect last) to avoid misclassifying.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Calls Node.is_node_constant on the address; if true returns
[ACCESS_BROADCAST, 0]. Calls extract_affine_form; if affine, returns
[CONTIGUOUS or STRIDED based on coefficient, stride value]. Calls
has_indirect_addressing; if true returns [GATHER/SCATTER]. Otherwise
returns [ACCESS_RANDOM, 0]. Return value is a 2-element List.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(depth) where depth is the height of the address-computation DAG.
Calls extract_affine_form (also O(depth)) and has_indirect_addressing.
Integer-only arithmetic; no Float dependency.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure analysis on validated graph nodes; no I/O, no mutation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "classify_address_pattern" that takes graph as Integer, address_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if address is constant (broadcast pattern)
    Let is_constant be proc is_node_constant from Node with address_node
    If is_constant is equal to true:
        Let result be proc create from List
        proc append from List with result, ACCESS_BROADCAST
        proc append from List with result, 0
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Try to extract affine form (base + stride*index)
    Let affine_info be extract_affine_form(graph, address_node)
    Let is_affine be proc get from List with affine_info, 0

    If is_affine is equal to true:
        Let stride be proc get from List with affine_info, 1

        Note: Stride=1 is contiguous, stride>1 is strided
        Let pattern_type be ACCESS_STRIDED
        If stride is equal to 1:
            Set pattern_type to ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS
        End If

        Set result to proc create from List
        proc append from List with result, pattern_type
        proc append from List with result, stride
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Check for indirect indexing (gather/scatter)
    Let has_indirect be has_indirect_addressing(graph, address_node)
    If has_indirect is equal to true:
        Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with address_node

        Note: Distinguish gather (load) vs scatter (store)
        Set pattern_type to ACCESS_GATHER
        If op_kind is equal to 41:
            Set pattern_type to ACCESS_SCATTER
        End If

        Set result to proc create from List
        proc append from List with result, pattern_type
        proc append from List with result, 1
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Default to random access
    Set result to proc create from List
    proc append from List with result, ACCESS_RANDOM
    proc append from List with result, 1
    Return result
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: GPU Memory Coalescing Detection
Note: ================================================================

Process called "detect_memory_coalescing" that takes graph as Integer, memory_ops as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    GPU memory coalescing occurs when threads in a warp access contiguous
    memory addresses in a single transaction.

    Requirements for coalescing:
    1. Threads access consecutive addresses
    2. Addresses are aligned to cache line (typically 128 bytes)
    3. Access width matches transaction size (32, 64, 128 bytes)

    Benefits:
    - Single memory transaction instead of 32 (warp size)
    - ~32x bandwidth improvement
    - Critical for GPU performance

    Analysis:
    - Check if all ops access contiguous memory
    - Verify alignment to cache line boundary
    - Compute wasted vs optimal transactions
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. For each memory operation, get access pattern
    2. Check if pattern is contiguous and aligned
    3. Compute number of memory transactions needed
    4. Compute optimal transaction count
    5. Calculate coalescing factor = optimal / actual
    6. Return CoalescingInfo structure
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(N * depth_of_address_DAG) where N = |memory_ops|. Each op invokes
    analyze_access_pattern. Hot path for any GPU-bound kernel analysis.
    The PPM-based coalescing factor uses integer math only, so it adds
    no floating-point dependency to stage1.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure analysis. Reads graph + node metadata; emits a fresh result
    struct. No system capability use. Assumes the caller has already
    validated that memory_ops contains only nodes from `graph`.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let coalescing_info be a value of type CoalescingInfo with
        is_coalesced as true,
        coalescing_factor_ppm as PPM_ONE,
        wasted_transactions as 0,
        optimal_transactions as 0

    Let op_count be proc length from List with memory_ops
    Let total_transactions be 0
    Let optimal_transactions be 0
    Let all_coalesced be true

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than op_count:
        Let mem_op be proc get from List with memory_ops, i

        Note: Analyze access pattern
        Let pattern be analyze_access_pattern(graph, mem_op)

        Note: Extract pattern info
        Let pattern_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with pattern, 0
        Let is_aligned be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with pattern, 24
        Let element_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with pattern, 16

        Note: Check if this operation coalesces
        Let op_coalesced be false
        If pattern_type is equal to ACCESS_CONTIGUOUS:
            If is_aligned is equal to true:
                Set op_coalesced to true
            End If
        End If

        If op_coalesced is equal to false:
            Set all_coalesced to false
        End If

        Note: Compute transaction count
        Note: Assume warp size = 32 threads
        Let warp_size be 32
        Let cache_line_size be 128

        If op_coalesced is equal to true:
            Note: Coalesced access - one transaction per cache line
            Let bytes_accessed be warp_size multiplied by element_size
            Let transactions be bytes_accessed divided by cache_line_size
            If bytes_accessed modulo by cache_line_size is greater than 0:
                Set transactions to transactions plus 1
            End If

            Set total_transactions to total_transactions plus transactions
            Set optimal_transactions to optimal_transactions plus transactions
        End If

        If op_coalesced is equal to false:
            Note: Uncoalesced - one transaction per thread
            Set total_transactions to total_transactions plus warp_size
            Set optimal_transactions to optimal_transactions plus 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with coalescing_info, 0, all_coalesced
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with coalescing_info, 24, optimal_transactions

    Note: Compute wasted transactions
    Let wasted be total_transactions minus optimal_transactions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with coalescing_info, 16, wasted

    Note: Compute coalescing factor as PPM (parts per million).
    Note: factor_ppm = (optimal * 1_000_000) / total, clamped to [0, PPM_ONE].
    Let factor_ppm be PPM_ONE
    If total_transactions is greater than 0:
        Let optimal_scaled be optimal_transactions multiplied by PPM_ONE
        Set factor_ppm to optimal_scaled divided by total_transactions
        If factor_ppm is greater than PPM_ONE:
            Set factor_ppm to PPM_ONE
        End If
        If factor_ppm is less than 0:
            Set factor_ppm to 0
        End If
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with coalescing_info, 8, factor_ppm

    Return coalescing_info
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Cache Locality Analysis
Note: ================================================================

Process called "compute_cache_locality" that takes graph as Integer, memory_ops as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Cache locality has two forms:
    - Spatial locality: Accessing nearby memory addresses (same cache line)
    - Temporal locality: Reusing same addresses over time (cache hits)

    Measurement:
    - Spatial: Ratio of unique cache lines to total accesses
    - Temporal: Average reuse distance (accesses between reuses)
    - Working set: Unique addresses accessed

    Good locality:
    - High spatial: Most accesses hit same cache lines (contiguous)
    - High temporal: Addresses reused quickly (small reuse distance)
    - Small working set: Fits in cache
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Track unique cache lines accessed
    2. Track access sequence for reuse distance
    3. Compute spatial locality = unique_lines / total_accesses
    4. Compute temporal locality from reuse distance
    5. Compute working set size
    6. Return LocalityInfo structure
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(N) memory ops with O(1) dict operations per op for cache-line set
    bucketing. Reuse-distance pass is O(N) plus dict size for unique
    address tracking. Locality info structs are reused via integer fields
    only (no Float dependency).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure analysis on validated graph nodes. No mutation of `graph`. Caller
    is responsible for ensuring memory_ops contains only Load (40) and
    Store (41) nodes from `graph`.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let locality_info be a value of type LocalityInfo with
        spatial_locality_ppm as PPM_ZERO,
        temporal_locality_ppm as PPM_ZERO,
        cache_reuse_distance as 0,
        working_set_size as 0

    Let cache_line_size be 64
    Let unique_cache_lines be proc create from Dict
    Let access_sequence be proc create from List
    Let unique_addresses be proc create from Dict

    Let op_count be proc length from List with memory_ops

    Note: Analyze each memory operation
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than op_count:
        Let mem_op be proc get from List with memory_ops, i

        Note: Address abstraction: prefer the address-producing input edge's
        Note: source node when available (matches how analyze_access_pattern
        Note: extracts the address expression). When no input edge is present
        Note: (rare; only constants or graph-roots), fall back to the
        Note: operation node identity itself which is a stable abstract
        Note: address suitable for set-based cache-line bucketing.
        Let mem_op_inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with mem_op
        Let mem_op_in_count be proc length from List with mem_op_inputs
        Let address be mem_op
        If mem_op_in_count is greater than 0:
            Let mem_op_addr_edge be proc get from List with mem_op_inputs, 0
            Set address to proc get_edge_source from Edge with mem_op_addr_edge
            If address is equal to 0:
                Set address to mem_op
            End If
        End If

        Note: Track unique addresses for working set
        proc set from Dict with unique_addresses, address, 1

        Note: Compute cache line (address / cache_line_size)
        Let cache_line be address divided by cache_line_size

        Note: Track unique cache lines
        proc set from Dict with unique_cache_lines, cache_line, 1

        Note: Track access sequence for reuse analysis
        proc append from List with access_sequence, address

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute spatial locality as PPM. The fraction here is
    Note: (unique_cache_lines / total_accesses). Lower fractions indicate
    Note: higher spatial locality (more accesses falling within already-touched
    Note: cache lines), so we invert the raw ratio to keep "higher = better".
    Let unique_line_count be proc size from Dict with unique_cache_lines
    Let total_accesses be op_count

    Let spatial_ppm be PPM_ONE
    If total_accesses is greater than 0:
        Let unique_scaled be unique_line_count multiplied by PPM_ONE
        Let raw_ratio_ppm be unique_scaled divided by total_accesses
        If raw_ratio_ppm is greater than PPM_ONE:
            Set raw_ratio_ppm to PPM_ONE
        End If
        Set spatial_ppm to PPM_ONE minus raw_ratio_ppm
        If spatial_ppm is less than 0:
            Set spatial_ppm to 0
        End If
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with locality_info, 0, spatial_ppm

    Note: Compute temporal locality (PPM) from reuse distance
    Let reuse_info be compute_reuse_distance(access_sequence)
    Let avg_reuse_distance be proc get from List with reuse_info, 0
    Let temporal_ppm be proc get from List with reuse_info, 1

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with locality_info, 16, avg_reuse_distance
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with locality_info, 8, temporal_ppm

    Note: Compute working set size
    Let working_set_size be proc size from Dict with unique_addresses multiplied by 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with locality_info, 24, working_set_size

    Return locality_info
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Shared Memory Opportunities
Note: ================================================================

Process called "detect_shared_memory_opportunity" that takes graph as Integer, memory_ops as Integer returns Boolean:
    @Reasoning
    Shared memory (GPU scratchpad) is beneficial when:
    1. Data is reused multiple multiplied by (high temporal locality)
    2. Multiple threads access same data (data sharing)
    3. Working set fits in shared memory (~48KB typical)
    4. Access pattern benefits from explicit control

    Detection:
    - Analyze reuse: same address accessed by multiple threads
    - Check working set size < shared memory size
    - Verify access pattern is regular (not completely random)
    - Estimate benefit vs overhead of copying to shared memory
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Analyze reuse across memory operations
    2. Compute working set size
    3. Check if working set fits in shared memory
    4. Verify sufficient reuse to amortize copy cost
    5. Return true if shared memory beneficial
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Wraps compute_cache_locality so cost is dominated by that pass.
    Threshold check uses integer comparison only (PPM-domain).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure predicate. No I/O, no mutation. Trusts graph node validity.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Compute locality info
    Let locality be compute_cache_locality(graph, memory_ops)

    Note: Extract reuse distance and working set
    Let reuse_distance be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with locality, 16
    Let working_set_size be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with locality, 24

    Note: Shared memory size limit (typical: 48KB)
    Let shared_mem_limit be 49152

    Note: Check if working set fits
    If working_set_size is greater than shared_mem_limit:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for sufficient reuse (reuse distance < threshold)
    Let reuse_threshold be 100
    If reuse_distance is greater than reuse_threshold:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check temporal locality (high reuse). PPM_HALF == 500_000 == 0.5.
    Let temporal_locality_ppm be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with locality, 8
    Let locality_threshold_ppm be 500000

    If temporal_locality_ppm is greater than locality_threshold_ppm:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Bank Conflict Detection
Note: ================================================================

Process called "analyze_bank_conflicts" that takes graph as Integer, shared_mem_ops as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    GPU shared memory is divided into banks (typically 32).
    Bank conflicts occur when multiple threads access different addresses
    in the same bank simultaneously, causing serialization.

    Conflict detection:
    - Address bank = (address / 4) % 32 (for 4-byte elements)
    - Conflict if threads access different addresses in same bank
    - Degree = max threads accessing same bank simultaneously

    Patterns:
    - Stride = bank_count → severe conflicts
    - Stride = 1 → no conflicts (broadcast if same address)
    - Stride power-of-2 → potential conflicts
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. For each shared memory access, extract address pattern
    2. Compute bank index for each thread
    3. Detect conflicts (different addresses, same bank)
    4. Compute conflict degree (serialization factor)
    5. Return BankConflictInfo structure
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(N * 32) for N memory ops (32 = warp size). Hot path for GPU code
    generation analyses; uses integer modulo arithmetic only.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure analysis on validated nodes; no I/O, no mutation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let conflict_info be a value of type BankConflictInfo with
        has_conflicts as false,
        conflict_degree as 1,
        conflict_pattern as 0

    Let bank_count be 32
    Let element_size be 4

    Let op_count be proc length from List with shared_mem_ops

    Let max_conflict_degree be 1
    Let any_conflicts be false

    Note: Analyze each shared memory operation
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than op_count:
        Let mem_op be proc get from List with shared_mem_ops, i

        Note: Get access pattern
        Let pattern be analyze_access_pattern(graph, mem_op)
        Let stride be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with pattern, 8

        Note: Simulate warp access (32 threads)
        Let warp_size be 32
        Let bank_access_count be proc create from Dict

        Note: For each thread, compute bank
        Let thread_id be 0
        While thread_id is less than warp_size:
            Note: Address for this thread = base + thread_id * stride * element_size
            Let byte_offset be thread_id multiplied by stride multiplied by element_size

            Note: Bank = (byte_offset / element_size) % bank_count
            Let element_offset be byte_offset divided by element_size
            Let bank be element_offset modulo by bank_count

            Note: Track accesses per bank
            Let current_count be proc get from Dict with bank_access_count, bank
            If current_count is equal to 0:
                Set current_count to 0
            End If
            Set current_count to current_count plus 1
            proc set from Dict with bank_access_count, bank, current_count

            Set thread_id to thread_id plus 1
        End While

        Note: Find maximum accesses to any bank (conflict degree)
        Let bank_keys be proc keys from Dict with bank_access_count
        Let bank_key_count be proc length from List with bank_keys

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than bank_key_count:
            Set bank to proc get from List with bank_keys, j
            Let access_count be proc get from Dict with bank_access_count, bank

            If access_count is greater than 1:
                Set any_conflicts to true
                If access_count is greater than max_conflict_degree:
                    Set max_conflict_degree to access_count
                End If
            End If

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with conflict_info, 0, any_conflicts
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with conflict_info, 8, max_conflict_degree

    Return conflict_info
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Memory Footprint Calculation
Note: ================================================================

Process called "compute_memory_footprint" that takes graph as Integer, nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes total memory requirements for a computation graph.

    Calculation:
    - Total bytes: Sum of all buffer sizes
    - Read bytes: Total data read from memory
    - Write bytes: Total data written to memory
    - Peak usage: Maximum simultaneous live buffers

    Uses:
    - Resource allocation planning
    - Determine if computation fits in device memory
    - Estimate bandwidth requirements
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. For each node, compute output buffer size
    2. Track read/write operations and sizes
    3. Perform liveness analysis for peak usage
    4. Sum all memory requirements
    5. Return MemoryFootprint structure
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(N) for the buffer-size pass plus the cost of compute_peak_memory_usage
    (also O(N)). All integer arithmetic.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure analysis. No I/O. Caller trusts graph node validity.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let footprint be a value of type MemoryFootprint with
        total_bytes as 0,
        reads_bytes as 0,
        writes_bytes as 0,
        peak_usage as 0

    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes

    Let total_bytes be 0
    Let reads_bytes be 0
    Let writes_bytes be 0

    Note: Compute total and read/write bytes
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with nodes, i

        Note: Get output type and size
        Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
        Let type_size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with output_type

        Note: Add to total
        Set total_bytes to total_bytes plus type_size

        Note: Check if load or store
        Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with node

        If op_kind is equal to 40:
            Note: Load operation
            Set reads_bytes to reads_bytes plus type_size
        End If

        If op_kind is equal to 41:
            Note: Store operation
            Set writes_bytes to writes_bytes plus type_size
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with footprint, 0, total_bytes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with footprint, 8, reads_bytes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with footprint, 16, writes_bytes

    Note: Compute peak usage via liveness analysis
    Let peak be compute_peak_memory_usage(graph, nodes)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with footprint, 24, peak

    Return footprint
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Memory Space Inference
Note: ================================================================

Process called "infer_memory_space" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Automatically infers the best memory space for data.

    Memory hierarchy:
    - Local (registers): Thread-private, fastest, very limited (~64KB/SM)
    - Shared (scratchpad): Block-shared, fast, limited (~48KB)
    - Constant: Read-only, cached, good for broadcast (64KB)
    - Global: Large, slow, but abundant (GBs)

    Inference rules:
    1. Constant data → CONSTANT memory
    2. Thread-private, scalar → LOCAL (registers)
    3. Shared across threads, high reuse → SHARED memory
    4. Large buffers, no sharing → GLOBAL memory
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Check if data is constant → CONSTANT
    2. Check if data is thread-local → LOCAL
    3. Check for sharing and reuse → SHARED
    4. Default to GLOBAL
    5. Return memory space constant
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(successors) per node for the SHARED-memory heuristic; otherwise O(1).
    Hot path during code generation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure inference. No I/O, no graph mutation.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Check if node is constant
    Let is_constant be proc is_node_constant from Node with node
    If is_constant is equal to true:
        Return MEMORY_CONSTANT
    End If

    Note: Get output type and size
    Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
    Let type_size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with output_type

    Note: Small scalars can go in registers (local memory)
    Let register_limit be 16
    If type_size is less than or equal to register_limit:
        Let is_scalar be proc is_primitive_type from Node with output_type
        If is_scalar is equal to true:
            Return MEMORY_LOCAL
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for sharing opportunity (high reuse, fits in shared mem).
    Note: Reuse is approximated as the consumer count of this node: a value
    Note: read by 4+ consumers is amortizing the cost of copying it into
    Note: shared memory across enough reads to make the copy profitable.
    Note: This is the standard "reuse > 1/x" heuristic from GPU literature
    Note: applied with x=4 to match the cost ratio between a coalesced
    Note: global load (single transaction per warp) and a shared-memory
    Note: hit (free after the initial copy).
    Let shared_mem_limit be 49152
    If type_size is less than shared_mem_limit:
        Let users be proc get_node_successors from Graph with graph, node
        Let user_count be proc length from List with users

        If user_count is greater than 3:
            Return MEMORY_SHARED
        End If
    End If

    Note: Default to global memory
    Return MEMORY_GLOBAL
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Streaming Pattern Detection
Note: ================================================================

Process called "detect_streaming_pattern" that takes graph as Integer, nodes as Integer returns Boolean:
    @Reasoning
    Streaming pattern: Data flows through pipeline stages with
    limited reuse. Common in:
    - Signal processing (filters, FFT)
    - Video processing (frame pipeline)
    - FPGA designs (dataflow architecture)

    Characteristics:
    - Linear data flow (inputs → stages → outputs)
    - Limited working set per stage
    - Sequential processing of data batches
    - Minimal feedback loops

    Detection:
    - Check for linear chain structure
    - Verify limited reuse (low temporal locality)
    - Check for batch processing (array inputs/outputs)
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Check if nodes form linear chain
    2. Verify limited reuse (temporal locality < threshold)
    3. Check for array/tensor data (batch processing)
    4. Return true if streaming pattern detected
    @End Implementation

    Note: Create subgraph from nodes
    Let subgraph be proc get_subgraph from Graph with graph, nodes

    Note: Check for linear chain structure
    Let is_linear be check_linear_structure(subgraph)
    If is_linear is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Extract memory operations
    Let memory_ops be extract_memory_operations_from_nodes(nodes)

    Note: Analyze locality
    Let locality be compute_cache_locality(graph, memory_ops)
    Let temporal_locality_ppm be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with locality, 8

    Note: Streaming has low temporal locality (data used once).
    Note: 0.3 in PPM == 300_000.
    Let streaming_threshold_ppm be 300000
    If temporal_locality_ppm is greater than streaming_threshold_ppm:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check for batch processing (array data)
    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes
    Let array_count be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
        Let is_array be is_array_type(output_type)

        If is_array is equal to true:
            Set array_count to array_count plus 1
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Most nodes should process arrays for streaming.
    Note: ratio_ppm = (array_count * 1_000_000) / node_count; threshold 700_000 == 0.7.
    Let array_ratio_ppm be 0
    If node_count is greater than 0:
        Let scaled be array_count multiplied by PPM_ONE
        Set array_ratio_ppm to scaled divided by node_count
    End If
    Let streaming_ratio_threshold_ppm be 700000
    If array_ratio_ppm is greater than streaming_ratio_threshold_ppm:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Alignment Analysis
Note: ================================================================

Process called "analyze_alignment" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Boolean:
    @Reasoning
    Memory alignment is critical for:
    - GPU coalescing (128-byte alignment for optimal coalescing)
    - SIMD loads (16-byte alignment for SSE/AVX)
    - Atomic operations (natural alignment required)

    Verification:
    - Check base address alignment
    - Verify stride preserves alignment
    - Consider element size
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Get address computation
    2. Check if base address is aligned
    3. Verify stride maintains alignment
    4. Check element size is power-of-2
    5. Return true if properly aligned
    @End Implementation

    Note: Get address computation
    Let inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with node
    If proc length from List with inputs is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let address_node be proc get from List with inputs, 0

    Note: Get element size
    Let output_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
    Let element_size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with output_type

    Note: Check if element size is power-of-2
    Let is_pow2 be is_power_of_two(element_size)
    If is_pow2 is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check alignment
    Let is_aligned be check_alignment(address_node, element_size)

    Return is_aligned
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Bandwidth Estimation
Note: ================================================================

Process called "compute_bandwidth_requirement" that takes graph as Integer, nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Estimates memory bandwidth required for computation.

    Formula:
    - Bandwidth (MB/s) = Total bytes transferred / Execution time (seconds)
    - Total bytes = Reads + Writes
    - Execution time estimated from operation count and throughput

    Result is returned in MB/s as an Integer to preserve precision until the
    v0.0.8.6 Float type lands. Callers wanting GB/s can divide by 1024 (binary)
    or 1000 (decimal).

    Uses:
    - Determine if computation is memory-bound
    - Verify device bandwidth is sufficient
    - Guide optimization (reduce transfers vs improve compute)
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Compute memory footprint (total reads + writes)
    2. Estimate execution time from operation counts (milliseconds)
    3. Calculate bandwidth_bytes_per_sec = (total_bytes * 1000) / time_ms
    4. Convert to MB/s by dividing by 1_048_576 (1024 * 1024) for binary MB
    5. Return bandwidth in MB/s
    @End Implementation

    Note: Compute memory footprint
    Let footprint be compute_memory_footprint(graph, nodes)
    Let reads be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with footprint, 8
    Let writes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with footprint, 16
    Let total_bytes be reads plus writes

    Note: Estimate execution time in milliseconds
    Let estimated_time_ms be estimate_execution_time(nodes)

    If estimated_time_ms is less than or equal to 0:
        Note: Zero/negative time means an unmeasurable burst; surface as 0 MB/s
        Note: rather than dividing by zero. Caller can treat as "unknown".
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Bandwidth in bytes/second = (total_bytes * 1000) / time_ms.
    Note: Convert to MB/s by dividing by 1_048_576.
    Let bytes_per_sec be total_bytes multiplied by 1000
    Set bytes_per_sec to bytes_per_sec divided by estimated_time_ms
    Let bandwidth_mbs be bytes_per_sec divided by 1048576

    Return bandwidth_mbs
End Process

Note: ================================================================
Note: Helper Functions
Note: ================================================================

Process called "extract_affine_form" that takes graph as Integer, address_node as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Extracts the affine form of an address expression: addr = base + stride * index.
    In Bifrost's graph IR, an address node is affine iff it is one of:
      (a) An Input/Constant node: stride = 0 (broadcast).
      (b) An Add node with one Constant operand and one Input/induction
          variable operand: stride = 1 (contiguous).
      (c) A Multiply node with a Constant scale: stride = constant.
      (d) An Add whose right operand is a Multiply(const, IV): stride = const.

    For non-affine forms (e.g. a Load in the address chain, i.e. gather/
    scatter via indirection), we return is_affine=false. The caller
    treats that as RANDOM/GATHER/SCATTER per classify_address_pattern.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. If the node is Constant (NodeType 0) or Input (NodeType 1): return [true, 0].
    2. If OpKind is Add (0) with at least 2 inputs, examine inputs:
       - If one is a Multiply(C, X) form, extract stride C from that.
       - Otherwise stride = 1.
    3. If OpKind is Multiply (2) with a constant first input, return [true, const_value].
    4. Otherwise return [false, 1].
    @End Implementation

    Let result be proc create from List

    If address_node is equal to 0:
        proc append from List with result, false
        proc append from List with result, 1
        Return result
    End If

    Let node_type be proc get_node_type from Node with address_node
    Note: Constant (0) or Input (1): pure broadcast, stride 0
    If node_type is equal to 0:
        proc append from List with result, true
        proc append from List with result, 0
        Return result
    End If
    If node_type is equal to 1:
        proc append from List with result, true
        proc append from List with result, 0
        Return result
    End If

    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with address_node
    Let addr_inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with address_node
    Let in_count be proc length from List with addr_inputs

    Note: Add (OpKind 0) with two operands: base + index*stride form
    If op_kind is equal to 0:
        If in_count is greater than or equal to 2:
            Let left_edge be proc get from List with addr_inputs, 0
            Let right_edge be proc get from List with addr_inputs, 1
            Let left_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with left_edge
            Let right_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with right_edge

            Let right_op be proc get_node_opkind from Node with right_src
            Note: If right operand is Multiply, try to extract its constant scale
            If right_op is equal to 2:
                Let mul_inputs be proc get_node_inputs from Node with right_src
                Let mul_in_count be proc length from List with mul_inputs
                If mul_in_count is greater than or equal to 2:
                    Let mul_left_edge be proc get from List with mul_inputs, 0
                    Let mul_left_src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with mul_left_edge
                    Let mul_left_type be proc get_node_type from Node with mul_left_src
                    If mul_left_type is equal to 0:
                        Note: Constant scale at offset 8 of constant payload
                        Let const_stride be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mul_left_src, 8
                        proc append from List with result, true
                        proc append from List with result, const_stride
                        Return result
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            Note: Plain base + index, stride = 1
            proc append from List with result, true
            proc append from List with result, 1
            Return result
        End If
    End If

    Note: Multiply (OpKind 2) with a constant scale
    If op_kind is equal to 2:
        If in_count is greater than or equal to 2:
            Let mul_e0 be proc get from List with addr_inputs, 0
            Let mul_s0 be proc get_edge_source from Edge with mul_e0
            Let mul_t0 be proc get_node_type from Node with mul_s0
            If mul_t0 is equal to 0:
                Let stride0 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mul_s0, 8
                proc append from List with result, true
                proc append from List with result, stride0
                Return result
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Not provably affine
    proc append from List with result, false
    proc append from List with result, 1
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning
Detects whether the address computation contains an indirect load
(scatter/gather pattern). Indirect addressing changes the access pattern
classification from STRIDED/CONTIGUOUS to GATHER and disables coalescing
on most GPUs. The detection is intentionally shallow - only checks the
immediate address node - because the affine extractor handles deeper
indirection.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Reads the address_node's OpKind. Returns true if it equals 40 (Load),
indicating the address is being computed via a memory load (indirect).
Returns false otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) - single OpKind read.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "has_indirect_addressing" that takes graph as Integer, address_node as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if address computation contains load operation
    Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with address_node

    If op_kind is equal to 40:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

Process called "check_alignment" that takes address_node as Integer, element_size as Integer returns Boolean:
    @Reasoning
    An address is aligned to element_size iff every term in its affine form
    contributes a multiple of element_size. We require:
      (a) The base (and any non-stride term) is a Constant divisible by
          element_size, or an Input we have to trust (Input parameters
          are always required to be element-aligned per Bifrost's
          ABI contract — declared on the kernel entry point).
      (b) The stride (if present) is a multiple of element_size.

    Without inter-procedural analysis we treat Inputs as aligned by
    contract and verify only the constant components we can see.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. If element_size <= 0, alignment is trivially undefined; return false.
    2. If element_size is not itself a power-of-2, accelerator alignment
       is not generally satisfiable; return false.
    3. Extract the affine form via extract_affine_form.
    4. If non-affine: not aligned.
    5. Otherwise check stride % element_size == 0. Base alignment is
       guaranteed by Input/Constant nodes (Inputs by ABI; Constants we
       can check directly when they appear as base).
    @End Implementation

    If element_size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    If is_power_of_two(element_size) is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Let affine_info be extract_affine_form(0, address_node)
    Let is_affine be proc get from List with affine_info, 0
    If is_affine is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Let stride be proc get from List with affine_info, 1

    Note: stride must be a multiple of element_size for aligned access
    If stride is less than 0:
        Return false
    End If
    Let stride_remainder be stride modulo by element_size
    If stride_remainder is not equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: For Constant base nodes we can additionally verify divisibility.
    Let base_type be proc get_node_type from Node with address_node
    If base_type is equal to 0:
        Let base_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with address_node, 8
        If base_value is less than 0:
            Return false
        End If
        Let base_remainder be base_value modulo by element_size
        If base_remainder is not equal to 0:
            Return false
        End If
    End If

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning
Computes the average reuse distance across an access sequence - the
number of distinct intervening accesses between successive references
to the same address. Reuse distance is the canonical metric for
temporal locality; lower distances indicate better cache-hit prospects.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates reuse_distances and last_access Dicts. Walks the
access_sequence; for each address, reads last_access[address]; if
non-zero, computes distance = i - last_pos and stores it in
reuse_distances. Always updates last_access[address] = i. After the
walk, computes the average of all reuse_distances values and returns
it. Returns 0 for an empty sequence.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(N) where N is the access_sequence length, plus O(N) Dict operations.
Space O(unique addresses).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure analysis on caller-owned data; no I/O.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_reuse_distance" that takes access_sequence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compute average reuse distance
    Let reuse_distances be proc create from Dict
    Let last_access be proc create from Dict

    Let seq_length be proc length from List with access_sequence

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than seq_length:
        Let address be proc get from List with access_sequence, i

        Note: Check if address was accessed before
        Let last_pos be proc get from Dict with last_access, address

        If last_pos is not equal to 0:
            Note: Compute reuse distance
            Let distance be i minus last_pos
            proc set from Dict with reuse_distances, address, distance
        End If

        Note: Update last access position
        proc set from Dict with last_access, address, i

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute average reuse distance
    Let total_distance be 0
    Let count be proc size from Dict with reuse_distances

    If count is equal to 0:
        Let result be proc create from List
        proc append from List with result, 0
        proc append from List with result, PPM_ZERO
        Return result
    End If

    Let distance_keys be proc keys from Dict with reuse_distances

    Let j be 0
    While j is less than count:
        Let key be proc get from List with distance_keys, j
        Set distance to proc get from Dict with reuse_distances, key
        Set total_distance to total_distance plus distance
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Let avg_distance be total_distance divided by count

    Note: Compute temporal locality as PPM (inverse of distance, normalized).
    Note: temporal_ppm = PPM_ONE - (avg_distance * PPM_ONE / max_distance), floored at 0.
    Let max_distance be 1000
    Let scaled_distance be avg_distance multiplied by PPM_ONE
    Let distance_ppm be scaled_distance divided by max_distance
    Let temporal_ppm be PPM_ONE minus distance_ppm
    If temporal_ppm is less than 0:
        Set temporal_ppm to 0
    End If
    If temporal_ppm is greater than PPM_ONE:
        Set temporal_ppm to PPM_ONE
    End If

    Set result to proc create from List
    proc append from List with result, avg_distance
    proc append from List with result, temporal_ppm
    Return result
End Process

Process called "compute_peak_memory_usage" that takes graph as Integer, nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the peak simultaneous live memory across the node list using a
    classical liveness-based sweep. For each node in topological order:
      * Walking value comes alive at definition.
      * It dies after its last consumer use.
    The peak is the maximum sum of byte sizes of live values at any point.

    This is the standard SSA-style liveness peak computation; on a DAG of
    N nodes it runs in O(N * avg_successors). The result is a tight upper
    bound on resident memory at any execution point of the kernel.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Iterate nodes in given (topological) order.
    2. Maintain a `live` dictionary mapping node -> remaining_consumer_count.
    3. At each step:
         (a) Add new node's size to current_live_bytes and record it.
         (b) For each input, decrement its remaining counter; if it hits
             zero, subtract its size from current_live_bytes.
       Track max current_live_bytes seen.
    @End Implementation

    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes
    If node_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let remaining_uses be proc create from Dict
    Let node_size be proc create from Dict

    Note: First pass: precompute sizes and use counts.
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Let out_type be proc get_node_output_type from Node with node
        Let size be proc get_type_size_bytes from Node with out_type
        proc set from Dict with node_size, node, size

        Let succs be proc get_node_successors from Graph with graph, node
        Let succ_count be proc length from List with succs
        proc set from Dict with remaining_uses, node, succ_count
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Second pass: sweep liveness in order.
    Let current_live be 0
    Let peak be 0

    Set i to 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node2 be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Let size2 be proc get from Dict with node_size, node2
        Set current_live to current_live plus size2

        If current_live is greater than peak:
            Set peak to current_live
        End If

        Note: Visit each input edge; the source's remaining_uses decreases.
        Let in_edges be proc get_node_inputs from Node with node2
        Let in_count be proc length from List with in_edges
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than in_count:
            Let in_edge be proc get from List with in_edges, k
            Let src be proc get_edge_source from Edge with in_edge
            Let prev_remaining be proc get from Dict with remaining_uses, src
            If prev_remaining is greater than 0:
                Let new_remaining be prev_remaining minus 1
                proc set from Dict with remaining_uses, src, new_remaining
                If new_remaining is equal to 0:
                    Let src_size be proc get from Dict with node_size, src
                    If src_size is greater than 0:
                        Set current_live to current_live minus src_size
                        If current_live is less than 0:
                            Set current_live to 0
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return peak
End Process

@Reasoning
Filters a node list down to memory operations (Load and Store ops). Used
by higher-level analyses (compute_memory_footprint, compute_bandwidth_requirement)
that only need the memory-op subset.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a fresh memory_ops List. Walks the input nodes list; for each
node reads OpKind and appends it to memory_ops if it equals 40 (Load) or
41 (Store). Returns memory_ops.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(N) where N is the input node count.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read; allocates one fresh List owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "extract_memory_operations_from_nodes" that takes nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    Let memory_ops be proc create from List

    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with node

        Note: Load=40, Store=41
        If op_kind is equal to 40:
            proc append from List with memory_ops, node
        End If
        If op_kind is equal to 41:
            proc append from List with memory_ops, node
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return memory_ops
End Process

@Reasoning
Tests whether the graph has linear (chain) structure - each node has at
most one predecessor and one successor. Linear graphs are
trivially-streamable and can benefit from streaming-memory hints in
codegen.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walks Graph.get_all_nodes; for each node calls Graph.get_node_predecessors
and Graph.get_node_successors. Returns false if any node has more than
one predecessor or more than one successor. Returns true if every node
satisfies the linear-chain constraint.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(V) - one pass over the node list with O(1) adjacency lookups.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read on graph state.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "check_linear_structure" that takes graph as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if graph is a linear chain
    Let all_nodes be proc get_all_nodes from Graph with graph
    Let node_count be proc length from List with all_nodes

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be proc get from List with all_nodes, i
        Let successors be proc get_node_successors from Graph with graph, node

        Note: Interior nodes should have exactly one successor
        Note: Last node can have zero successors
        If proc length from List with successors is greater than 1:
            Return false
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning
Tests whether a type pointer represents an array/aggregate type (Vector,
Matrix, or Tensor). Used by memory-footprint and bandwidth analyses to
decide whether to multiply through dimensions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns false for null type. Reads the discriminant at offset 0; returns
true if it equals 2 (Vector), 3 (Matrix), or 5 (Tensor), false
otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "is_array_type" that takes type_ptr as Integer returns Boolean:
    If type_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let discriminant be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_ptr, 0

    Note: Vector=2, Matrix=3, Tensor=5
    If discriminant is equal to 2:
        Return true
    End If
    If discriminant is equal to 3:
        Return true
    End If
    If discriminant is equal to 5:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

Process called "estimate_execution_time" that takes nodes as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Estimates total execution time (milliseconds) of a node list as the
    sum of per-node nominal cycle costs converted to milliseconds.
    The cycle costs come from the same OpKind-keyed table used elsewhere
    in Bifrost (arithmetic = 1, vector = 10, matrix = 100, conv/FFT = 500,
    memory = 50). At a nominal 1 GHz clock those map directly to ns;
    we sum and divide by 1_000_000 to get milliseconds.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Walk each node; accumulate the matching OpKind cycle cost.
    2. Convert total cycles to milliseconds (cycles / 1_000_000).
    3. Clamp to >= 1 ms so downstream callers never see zero time.
    @End Implementation

    Let node_count be proc length from List with nodes
    Let total_cycles be 0

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let n be proc get from List with nodes, i
        Let op_kind be proc get_node_opkind from Node with n

        Let cycles be 10
        If op_kind is greater than or equal to 0:
            If op_kind is less than or equal to 5:
                Set cycles to 1
            End If
        End If
        If op_kind is greater than or equal to 6:
            If op_kind is less than or equal to 9:
                Set cycles to 100
            End If
        End If
        If op_kind is greater than or equal to 10:
            If op_kind is less than or equal to 12:
                Set cycles to 10
            End If
        End If
        If op_kind is greater than or equal to 13:
            If op_kind is less than or equal to 18:
                Set cycles to 500
            End If
        End If
        If op_kind is greater than or equal to 34:
            If op_kind is less than or equal to 41:
                Set cycles to 50
            End If
        End If

        Set total_cycles to total_cycles plus cycles
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Convert cycles at 1 GHz nominal clock to milliseconds.
    Let time_ms be total_cycles divided by 1000000
    If time_ms is less than 1:
        Set time_ms to 1
    End If

    Return time_ms
End Process

Process called "is_power_of_two" that takes n as Integer returns Boolean:
    @Reasoning
    True iff n > 0 and n has exactly one bit set. We prove this by
    repeated halving: n is a power of two iff dividing by 2 always yields
    an exact quotient until we reach 1. Equivalent to the classical
    `n & (n - 1) == 0` bit-trick, expressed without a native bitwise-and
    primitive (stage1 codegen lacks it for Integer expressions).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    1. Reject n <= 0.
    2. Repeatedly halve n. If n is odd at any step other than the
       terminal value of 1, return false.
    3. Cap iterations at 64 to bound the loop on 64-bit operands.
    @End Implementation

    If n is less than or equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let x be n
    Let iterations be 0
    While x is greater than 1:
        Let remainder be x modulo by 2
        If remainder is not equal to 0:
            Return false
        End If
        Set x to x divided by 2
        Set iterations to iterations plus 1
        If iterations is greater than 64:
            Note: Safety cap; should never trigger for 64-bit Integers.
            Return false
        End If
    End While

    Return true
End Process
